  "prompt": "What is the chemical reaction when acetic acid is combined with sodium hydroxide (NaOH)?",
  "response": "The chemical reaction when acetic acid (CH\u2083COOH) is combined with sodium hydroxide (NaOH) is a neutralization reaction.  It forms sodium acetate (CH\u2083COONa) and water (H\u2082O).\n\nHere's the balanced chemical equation:\n\n**CH\u2083COOH (aq) + NaOH (aq) \u2192 CH\u2083COONa (aq) + H\u2082O (l)**\n\n*   **CH\u2083COOH (aq):** Acetic acid in aqueous solution (vinegar is a dilute solution of acetic acid)\n*   **NaOH (aq):** Sodium hydroxide in aqueous solution (a strong base, also known as lye or caustic soda)\n*   **CH\u2083COONa (aq):** Sodium acetate in aqueous solution (a salt)\n*   **H\u2082O (l):** Water in liquid form\n\n**In simpler terms:**\n\nAcid + Base \u2192 Salt + Water\n\nThe sodium hydroxide neutralizes the acetic acid, forming a salt (sodium acetate) and water. This reaction is exothermic, meaning it releases heat.\n",
